cant at varying degrees for different areas of the law such as evidence, inheritance, land, and marriage law. While there was inevitable conflict, the local normative order was as much a social fact for the early colonial rulers as Roman-Dutch law. This is contrary to the received wisdom of the ages that Roman-Dutch law was imposed on the Sinhalese of the maritime provinces under Dutch control. When translated into everyday lives, such adoption of plural practices could rebound on coloniser and colonised in unexpected ways, revealing the complexities of colonial law in practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLaw. 4aSouth Asia. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aDutch East India Company, VOC, Roman-Dutch Law, Colonial Law, History of Sri Lanka, Legal Pluralism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978940060424740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789400604247423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789400604247/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK